comments.text:
"Noisey Atlanta displays almost perfectly the production chain of the first 
type of music mentioned. The scene has a unique way of processing music: it 
goes straight from the producers hands to the big strip clubs like Magic 
City (Mike Will Made It specifically references this strip club when 
interviewed). From there it goes to usual clubs and onto radio, and the 
music gains listening time in that way. In an odd way, the strippers have a 
large influence over the type of hip hop blaring from the tracks: to 
paraphrase Drake, the women are quite literally running the game." for the 
full article, be sure to follow this link: 
https://nattyjahmsmusic.wordpress.com/2015/04/16/think-piece-the-dominance-of-atlanta/
﻿

Its so cool to see rappers soften so much. 
Im from the 80s and 90s.
Back then The big guy with that stupid hat on could have gotten his neck 
slapped for wearing that. Its good to see them change and dress up in that 
Forever 21, Zara  designs.
I remember Cypress Hill doing that psychedelic/stoner crazy thing in early 
90s, and then Eminem pulled that nerdy thing in the late 90s, I think it 
was the beginning of change in hip hop. After that, black rappers started 
wearing contact lenses, heavy metal t shirts and the likes. Writing crazy 
lyrics, even gay lyrics, to be crazier. 
I think its all cool. I know its all fashion, but young people become 
fashion victims. 
I rather listen to that than some fake gangster shit, anyways.﻿
